{"title_page": "Eat Bulaga!", "text_new": "{{Redirect|EB!|text=For other uses, see [[EB (disambiguation)|EB]]. It is not to be confused with [[EV (disambiguation)|EV]], or [[Eevee]], a Pok\u00e9mon.}}\n{{short description|Philippine television show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Eat Bulaga!\n| show_name_2 = Eat... Bulaga!\n| image = Eat Bulaga! title card.jpg\n| caption = Title card\n| genre = [[Variety show]]\n| director = {{Plainlist|\n* Bert de Leon\n* Poochie Rivera\n* Norman Ilacad\n* Pat Plaza\n* Moty Apostol}}\n| presenter = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tito Sotto]]\n* [[Vic Sotto]]\n* [[Joey de Leon]]}}\n| narrated = Tom Alvarez\n| theme_music_composer = {{plainlist|\n* Vincent Dy Buncio\n* Pancho Oppus\n* Vic Sotto}}\n| opentheme = \"Eat Bulaga!\"\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| num_episodes = 12,604 <!--as of March 14, 2020-->\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Helen Atienza-Dela Cruz\n* Sheila Macariola-Ilacad\n* Liza Marcelo-Lazatin\n* Maricel Carampatana-Vinarao}}\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| runtime = 150\u2013180 minutes\n| company = [[TAPE Inc.]]\n| network = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]] {{small|(1979\u20131989)}}\n* [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]  {{small|(1989\u20131995)}}\n* [[GMA Network]] {{small|(since 1995)}}}}\n| picture_format = {{plainlist|\n* [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n* [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])}}\n| first_aired = {{start date|1979|7|30}}\n| last_aired = present\n| related = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[The New Eat Bulaga! Indonesia]]''\n* ''Eat Bulaga! Myanmar''}}\n| website = https://www.eatbulaga.tv\n}}\n\n'''''Eat Bulaga!''''' ({{translation|Lunchtime  Surprise}}) formerly ''Eat... Bulaga!'' is a [[Philippine television]] variety show broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. Produced by [[TAPE Inc.]], it is the [[List of longest-running Philippine television series|longest running]] variety show in the Philippines with over 12,600 episodes. Originally hosted by [[Tito Sotto]], [[Vic Sotto]], [[Joey de Leon]], Chiqui Hollman and [[Richie D'Horsie]], it premiered on July 30, 1979. The show is also broadcast worldwide through [[GMA Pinoy TV]] and streaming online on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/eatbulaga1979 |title=Eat Bulaga! |website=YouTube |language=en |accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> Tito Sotto, Vic Sotto, de Leon, [[Jimmy Santos (actor)|Jimmy Santos]], [[Ruby Rodriguez]], [[Jose Manalo]], [[Allan K.]], [[Anjo Yllana]], [[Wally Bayola]], [[Paolo Ballesteros]], [[Pia Guanio]], [[Pauleen Luna]], [[Ryan Agoncillo]], [[Ryzza Mae Dizon]], [[Alden Richards]], [[Maine Mendoza]], [[Baste Granfon]], [[Luane Dy]], Echo Calingal and Kayla Rivera currently serve as hosts.\n\n==Overview==\n\n===Radio Philippines Network (1979\u20131989)===\n[[File:Eat Bulaga! TY.jpg|right|thumb|The show's original hosts.]]\nProduction Specialists, Inc., a company owned by Romy Jalosjos, came up with an idea of creating a noontime show for [[Radio Philippines Network]]. Antonio Tuviera pitched that [[Tito Sotto]], [[Vic Sotto]] and [[Joey de Leon]] would be the perfect hosts for the show. <ref name=\"kd\">{{cite AV media|people = Dantes, Dingdong (Host)|title=Kuwentong Dabarkads|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xnvtcw53WpM|medium=Documentary|publisher = GMA Network, Inc.|location=Philippines|date = 2011}}</ref> At a meeting at the [[InterContinental Manila]], Tuviera made an offer to them which was accepted.<ref name=\"kd\"/><ref name=\"peproad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/20047/Tito,-Vic-&-Joey-recall-their-road-to-success/1/1|title=Tito, Vic & Joey recall their road to success|last1=Garcia|first1=Rose|date=November 26, 2008|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc.|access-date=July 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Eat Bulaga!'' premiered on July 30, 1979, with its pilot episode filmed in RPN Live Studio 1 in Broadcast City.<ref name=\"peplong\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/features/14178/longest-running-television-shows|title=Longest running television shows |author=Godinez, Bong |date=October 24, 2007 |website=PEP.ph |publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc. |accessdate=July 22, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722230157/http://www.pep.ph/features/14178/longest-running-television-shows|archivedate=July 22, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"coffeebook\">{{cite book |last=Francisco|first=Butch|date=2011 |title=Eat Bulaga: Ang Unang Tatlong Dekada|publisher=TAPE, Inc.|isbn=9789719528302}}</ref> Chiqui Hollman<ref name=\"kd\"/> and [[Richie D'Horsie]] also served as the original hosts.<ref name=\"peplong\"/> The theme song was written by Vincent Dy Buncio and Pancho Oppus, while melody was composed by Vic Sotto and musically arranged by Homer Flores.<ref name=\"noontimeheat\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/79311/noontime-tv-landscape-the-battle-heats-up |title=Noontime TV landscape: The battle heats up |author=Policarpio, Allan |last2=San Diego Jr. |first2=Bayani |last3=Cruz |first3=Marinel |date=February 2, 2013 |website=Inquirer.net |publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer, Inc. |accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref> During the show's first few months, it was in the brink of cancellation due to competition and lacked of advertisers, despite having their advertising rates reduced to [[Philippine peso|\u20b1]]750 and the hosts' lack of salary for six months.<ref name=\"kd\"/>\n\nDe Leon said that he, Tito and Vic didn't sign a contract with the show, when they were offered to become hosts. Vic Sotto said that he accepted the offer and would stop, once he had money to buy a personal vehicle. De Leon also said that the show was supposed to be a short-term employment. After 2 years, Tito Sotto, Vic Sotto and de Leon decided to stay with the show.<ref name=\"pinoyparazzi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DMSBxNibA9g |title= Joey de Leon, wala raw kontrata sa 'Eat Bulaga'|website=Youtube|publisher=PinoyParazzi |date=June 9, 2014 |accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"historicvic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/31385/vic-sotto-says-being-part-of-eat-bulaga-makes-him-feel-like-a-historical-figure/1/1#focus|title=Vic Sotto says being part of Eat Bulaga! makes him feel like a \"historical figure\"|last1=Jimenez|first1=Jocelyn|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc.|date=October 7, 2011 |accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref> The show gained top-rating status in 1980 with the segment \"Mr. Macho.\"<ref name=\"kd\"/><ref name=\"coffeebook\"/> Production Specialists later handed production to [[TAPE, Inc.]]<ref name=\"philstar1\"/> In 1982, [[Coney Reyes]] joined the show as the newest host.<ref name=\"philstar1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/142832/noontime-shows-through-years|title=Noontime shows through the years|last1=Francisco|first1=Butch|website=Philstar Entertainment|publisher=Philstar|date=December 8, 2001 |accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[People Power Revolution]], the show went off the air from February 27, 1986 to March 1, 1986 as the transmitter of RPN had been shut down. In 1987, [[Aiza Seguerra]] joined the show after ''Little Miss Philippines''.<ref name=\"kd\"/><ref>{{cite episode|title=Little Miss Philippines: Aiza Seguerra|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L-xqueoTtwI|series =Eat... Bulaga!|airdate=1987|network=[[Radio Philippines Network]]||station=RPN-9}}</ref> The show left Broadcast City on December 2, 1987, and transferred to Celebrity Sports Plaza on December 3, 1987. The network was also beset by periodical change of management, leading to Tony Tuviera's decision to conduct negotiations with then-fledgling network [[ABS-CBN]] to eventually transfer the show.\n\n===Alto Broadcasting System - Chronicle Broadcasting Network (1989\u20131995)===\nIn 1989, ''Eat...Bulaga!'' moved to [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]<ref name=\"philstar1\"/> under a co-production agreement due to problems brought about by the [[Radio Philippines Network#First Downfall (1986-1989)|sequestration of RPN]].<ref name=\"peplong\"/> On February 18, 1989, the show premiered on ABS-CBN and was staged at [[Smart Araneta Coliseum|Araneta Coliseum]], with a TV special titled ''Eat... Bulaga!: Moving On''.<ref name=\"ebtahanan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QTJw7JrwlUk|title=#EBThrowback: Ang Tahanan ng Eat Bulaga!|date=December 7, 2018|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref> After its transfer to ABS-CBN, the show started airing from ABS-CBN Studio 1 at the [[ABS-CBN Broadcasting Center]]. During the show's special occasions, they were used the network's Studio 2 as a venue. The show's tenth anniversary was held on September 23, 1989 at Araneta Coliseum.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite episode|title=Eat Bulaga 10th Anniversary Opening Theme|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VMrT9yE2mXo|series =Eat... Bulaga!|airdate=September 23, 1989|network=[[ABS-CBN]]}}</ref> In 1991, [[Ruby Rodriguez]] and [[Rio Diaz]] became regular co-hosts. In 1994, ABS-CBN attempted to buy the airing rights of the show from TAPE Inc. Antonio Tuviera and Malou Choa-Fagar rejected the offer, leading to ABS-CBN giving an ultimatum to the show to leave the network in January 1995.\n\n=== GMA Network (since 1995) ===\nIn 1994, the show moved out from ABS-CBN Studio 1, and returned to Celebrity Sports Plaza, as preparation for the show's transfer to [[GMA Network]]. A contract signing between TAPE, Inc. and GMA officials was held at the [[Makati Shangri-La, Manila]] on January 19, 1995.<ref name=\"peplong\"/> The show made its premiere telecast on the Network on January 28, 1995 with a TV special titled ''Eat... Bulaga!: The Moving!''.<ref name=\"ebtahanan\"/><ref name=\"peplong\"/><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|title='Eat Bulaga' premieres on GMA-7|pages=197|newspaper=[[Manila Standard]]|location=Google News Archive|date =January 22, 1995|url =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZjpNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2552%2C4115779|accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Toni Rose Gayda]], [[Allan K]], Samantha Lopez and [[Francis Magalona]] became hosts in 1995, and [[Anjo Yllana]] in 1998. In 2000, ''Eat Bulaga!'' became the first to give away millions on Philippine television. The show introduced \"Laban o Bawi\" to its audience, and it became an instant hit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/features/12061/-eat-bulaga-and-27-years-of-making-the-pinoys-happy-|title=\"Eat...Bulaga!\" and 27 years of making the Pinoys happy!|last1=Almo|first1=Nerisa|date=March 20, 2007|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc.|access-date=July 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723133943/http://www.pep.ph/features/12061/-eat-bulaga-and-27-years-of-making-the-pinoys-happy-|archive-date=July 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In May 2001, Magalona was removed from the show following his arrest due to drug possession. [[Janno Gibbs]] served as his replacement. After his acquittal from the drug charges and subsequent rehabilitation, Magalona returned in 2002. In April 2002, the ratings of ''Eat Bulaga!'' surged following the popularity of the [[SexBomb Dancers]] and the segment ''Sige, Ano Kaya Mo? Sakmo!''. The 25th year celebration of the show was aired on November 19, 2004 from [[Expo Pilipino]].<ref name=\"lionsilver\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lionheartv.net/2010/03/eat-bulaga-silver-special-on-dvd/|title=Eat, Bulaga! silver special on DVD|date=March 11, 2010|website=LionhearTV|publisher=B&L Multimedia Co. Ltd.|access-date=July 22, 2015}}</ref> It won the Best Entertainment (One-Off/Annual) Special at the [[Asian Television Award]] in [[Singapore]] on December 1, 2005.<ref name=\"philroad\">{{cite web |url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/312499/eat-bulaga%C2%92s-road-victory|title=Eat, Bulaga!&#146;s road to victory|last1=Francisco|first1=Butch|date=December 17, 2005|website=Philstar Entertainment|publisher=Philstar|access-date=April 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/313518/more-asian-television-awards|title=More Asian Television Awards|last1=Francisco|first1=Butch|date=December 24, 2005|website=Philstar Entertainment|publisher=Philstar|access-date=July 22, 2015}}</ref> The presentation, titled ''Eat Bulaga Silver Special'', was broadcast on November 27, 2004 and November 29, 2004.<ref name=\"lionsilver\"/>\n\nIn 2005, ''Eat Bulaga!'' started airing worldwide through [[GMA Pinoy TV]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/international/articles/2015-07-28/683/GMA-international-channels-now-available-in-Charter-Spectrum-TV-in-the-US/|title=GMA international channels now available in Charter Spectrum TV in the US {{!}} GMA international channels now available in Charter Spectrum TV in the US|last=Inc.|first=GMA New Media|access-date=May 19, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In 2006, the [[SexBomb Girls]] left the show due to a dispute with the show's producers.<ref name=\"sexbombbabes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/389/sexbomb-returns-to-eat-bulaga-as-regular-performers|title=SexBomb returns to \"Eat Bulaga!\" as regular performers|last1=Borromeo|first1=Eric|date=March 12, 2007|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc.|access-date=July 22, 2015}}</ref> They were replaced by EB Babes in August.<ref name=\"sexbombbabes\"/> In March 2007, the SexBomb Girls returned to the show and would later leave in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pep.ph/news/12465/rivalry-between-sexbomb-and-eb-babes-heats-up|title=Rivalry between SexBomb and EB Babes heats up|last1=Nicasio|first1=Nonie|date=March 11, 2007|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc.|access-date=July 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/12522/eb-babe-kim-wala-namang-dapat-ikainsecure-ang-eb-babes-sa-sexbomb#cxrecs_s|title=EB Babe Kim: \"Wala namang dapat ika-insecure ang EB Babes sa SexBomb.\"|last1=Nicasio|first1=Nonie|date=March 16, 2007|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc.|access-date=July 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/3269/no-bad-blood-between-these-sexbombs |title=No bad blood between these SexBombs|last1=Cruz|first1=Marinel R.|website= Inquirer.net|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref> In September 2007, de Leon started an on-screen war with [[Willie Revillame]], which led to the [[Hello Pappy scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/58382/Joey-tells-Willie-Explain-before-you-complain |title=Joey tells Willie: Explain before you complain |date=August 30, 2007 |website=GMA News Online |publisher=GMA Network, Inc. |accessdate=April 11, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/58395/news/nation/roxas-seeks-probe-on-hello-pappy-game-show-controversy|title=Roxas seeks probe on 'Hello, Pappy' game show controversy|date=August 30, 2007|website=GMA News Online|publisher=GMA Network, Inc.|accessdate=July 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 6, 2009, [[Francis Magalona]], passed away due to [[leukemia]], and a tribute episode was held the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/21051/%3Cem%3EEat-Bulaga!-%3C-em%3Epays-tribute-to-Francis-M-tomorrow,-March-7/2|title=Eat Bulaga! pays tribute to Francis M tomorrow, March 7|date=March 6, 2007|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal|last1=Godinez|first1=Bong|accessdate=July 23, 2015}}</ref> [[Ryan Agoncillo]] joined the show later in 2009 and the show's 30th anniversary special, ''Tatlong Dekads ng Dabarkads'' aired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/473048/eat-bulaga-awards-cash-grants-scholars|title=Eat, Bulaga! awards cash & grants to scholars|date=June 1, 2009|website=Philstar Entertainment|publisher=Philstar|accessdate=July 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/467840/changing-lives-30-young-people|title=Changing the lives of 30 young people|last1=Francisco|first1=Butch|date=May 16, 2009|website=Philstar Entertainment|publisher=Philstar |accessdate=July 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Lenten drama specials returned<ref name=\"lenten specials\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2014/04/21/1314229/eb-dabarkads-show-dramatic-chops |last1=Salterio|first1=Leah C.|title=EB Dabarkads show dramatic chops|website=Philstar Entertainment|publisher=Philstar |date=April 21, 2014|accessdate=May 15, 2014}}</ref> and an annual awards ceremony, the ''Dabarkads Awards'' was first held.\n\nIn July 2015, the [[shipping (fandom)|love team]] [[AlDub]] started along with the segment, ''[[Kalyeserye]]''. The show tripled its Mega Manila and nationwide television ratings and became a daily trending topic on [[Twitter]] worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manilastandardtoday.com/2015/07/28/make-way-for-alden-and-yaya-dub/ |title=Make way for Alden and Yaya Dub |author=Wang, Nickie |date=July 28, 2015 |website=Manila Standard Today |publisher=Manila Standard Today |access-date=August 11, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803145808/http://manilastandardtoday.com/2015/07/28/make-way-for-alden-and-yaya-dub/ |archivedate=August 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/532149/showbiz/pep/pauleen-luna-aldub-has-brought-a-different-kind-of-energy-to-the-show|title=Pauleen Luna: 'AlDub has brought a different kind of energy to the show'|last1=Rula|first1=Gorgy|date=August 8, 2015|website=GMA News Online|publisher=GMA Network, Inc.|access-date=August 11, 2015}}</ref> The show held 10 out of 10 highest-rated episodes in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/agb/21244/agb-nielsen-mega-manila-ratings-october-4-13-2015-eat-bulaga-sweeps-10-out-of-10-highest-ratings-in-2015|title=AGB Nielsen Mega Manila Ratings (October 4-13, 2015): Eat Bulaga! sweeps 10 out of 10 highest ratings in 2015|last1=Ching|first1=Mark Angelo|website=PEP.ph|publisher=Philippine Entertainment Portal, Inc.|date=October 22, 2015|access-date=October 25, 2015}}</ref> The show held a [[benefit concert]] at the [[Philippine Arena]] on October 24, 2015. Dubbed as ''Sa Tamang Panahon'', its hashtag #ALDubEBTamangPanahon reached 41 million tweets,<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/181964/aldub-posts-record-breaking-41-m-tamang-panahon-tweets|title='AlDub' posts record-breaking 41-M 'Tamang Panahon' tweets|last1=Hegina|first1=Aries Joseph| website=Inquirer.net|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer, Inc.|date=October 26, 2015|access-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> becoming the most used hashtag within 24 hours on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2016/3/10-years-of-twitter-five-key-tweets-that-made-record-breaking-history-421461|title=10 years of Twitter: Five key tweets that made record-breaking history|last1=Lynch|first1=Kevin|website=[[Guinness World Records]]|publisher=Guinness World Records|date=March 21, 2016|access-date=March 21, 2016}}</ref> The segment ''Kalyeserye'' concluded on December 17, 2016 with a total of 400 episodes.\n\nOn December 8, 2018, ''Eat Bulaga!'' transferred to [[APT Studios]], located in [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], ending 23 years at the [[Broadway Centrum]].<ref name=\"eblooksback\">{{cite web |last1=Anarcon |first1=James Patrick |title=Eat Bulaga looks back on RPN-9, ABS-CBN days as it transfers to new studio |url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/28916/eat-bulaga-looks-back-on-rpn-9-abs-cbn-days-as-it-transfers-to-new-studio |website=PEP.ph |accessdate=January 6, 2019 |date=December 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Andrade |first1=Nel |title='Eat Bulaga' moving to Cainta, Rizal |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/12/05/eat-bulaga-moving-to-cainta-rizal/ |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |accessdate=December 7, 2018 |date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In March 2020, the admission of a live audience in the studio and production were suspended due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Eat Bulaga' bans live audience amid coronavirus scare |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/entertainment/2020/3/9/Eat-Bulaga-no-live-audience-coronavirus-covid.html |website=CNN Philippines |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=GMA 7 announces temporary suspension of entertainment program production|url=https://www.rappler.com/entertainment/news/253810-gma-temporary-suspension-entertainment-programs-coronavirus-metro-manila-lockdown|website=Rappler |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{multiple image\n|align = right\n|total_width = 450\n|direction = horizontal\n|header = Main hosts\n|image1 = Vicente_Sotto_III_(cropped).jpg\n|caption1 = Tito Sotto\n|height1 = 150\n|image2 = Vic_Sotto_in_Antipolo_City_on_July_23,_2017.jpg\n|caption2 = Vic Sotto\n|height2 = 150\n|image3 = Joey De Leon and Travis Kraft (cropped).jpg\n|caption3 = Joey de Leon\n|height3 = 150\n}}\n\n* [[Tito Sotto]] {{small|(since 1979)}}<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/tv/eat_bulaga/cast/ |title=Cast Eat Bulaga |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Vic Sotto]] {{small|(since 1979)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Joey de Leon]] {{small|(since 1979)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n\n===Co-hosts===\n* [[Jimmy Santos (actor)|Jimmy Santos]] {{small|(since 1983)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Ruby Rodriguez]] {{small|(since 1991)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Jose Manalo]] {{small|(since 1994)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Allan K.]] {{small|(since 1995)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Anjo Yllana]] {{small|(since 1999)}}\n* [[Wally Bayola]] {{small|(since 2000)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Paolo Ballesteros]] {{small|(since 2001)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Pia Guanio]] {{small|(since 2003)}}\n* [[Pauleen Luna]] {{small|(since 2004)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Ryan Agoncillo]] {{small|(since 2009)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Ryzza Mae Dizon]] {{small|(since 2012)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Alden Richards]] {{small|(since 2015)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Maine Mendoza]] {{small|(since 2015)}}<ref name=\"Cast\"/>\n* [[Baste Granfon]] {{small|(since 2015)}}\n* [[Luane Dy]] {{small|(since 2017)}}\n* Echo Calingal {{small|(since 2018)}}\n* Kayla Rivera {{small|(since 2019)}}\n\n;Macho Men\n* CJ Rada {{small|(since 2019)}}\n* Jonas Marabe {{small|(since 2019)}} \n* Ralmon Mendoza {{small|(since 2019)}}\n* Marlon Marcia {{small|(since 2019)}}\n* Czack Buenafe {{small|(since 2019)}}\n* Carlo Pasion {{small|(since 2019)}}\n* Pau Magnayon {{small|(since 2019)}}\n\n===Former cast===\n[[File:Jose Manalo, Paolo Ballesteros and Wally Bayola.jpg|alt=paolo    ballesteros|thumb|Jose Manalo, Wally Bayola, and Paolo Ballesteros serve as hosts]]\n* Adolf Garalde {{small|(2011\u20132013, Gong player)}}\n* [[Aicelle Santos]] {{small|(2016\u20132017)}}\n* [[Aiko Melendez]] {{small|(1989\u20131995)}}\n* [[Ai-Ai delas Alas]] {{small|(1995\u20132000)}}\n* Aileen Damiles<ref name=\"Eat Bulaga and Beauty Queens\">{{cite web |url=http://www.missosology.info/forum/viewtopic.php?f=15&t=133488&start=0|title=Eat Bulaga and Beauty Queens|date=April 22, 2012|publisher=Missosology|access-date=September 5, 2016}}</ref> \n* [[Aiza Seguerra]] {{small|(1987\u20131997)}}\n* Aji Estornino {{small|(2002)}}\n* [[Alfie Lorenzo]]<ref name=\"ebcoffeebook\">{{cite book |last=Francisco|first=Butch|date=2011 |title=Eat Bulaga!: Ang Unang Tatlong Dekada|publisher=TAPE, Inc.|pages=124\u2013125|others=Designed by Jako de Leon|isbn=9789719528302}}</ref>\n* [[Ali Sotto]] {{small|(1993\u20131994)}}\n* [[Alicia Mayer]] {{small|(2004\u20132006)}}\n* Amboy Valdez {{small|(2019, ''Maliit na Bagay'')}}\n* [[Amy Perez]] {{small|(1988\u20131995)}}\n* Ana Marie Craig {{small|(1996)}}\n* Angela Luz {{small|(1989\u20131995)}}\n* [[Angelu de Leon]]\n* [[Anne Curtis]] {{small|(2004)}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://